My love for Thai food meant I have some very high expectations, and this place did not disappoint.

It is hard to define Lovely Day in the first place. It is, for sure, not trendy. But despite its dim & aging interior, it is not mundane either. In fact, the crowd we've seen is still overwhelmingly the young and hip Nolita type. They approved this over $60 brunch? Unknowable universe!

This place passed my curry test for how spicy it was. I did not see this coming - it was disguised as a green curry, which is typically less spicy than red curry. What kind of chili was that?

They also make some of the best Pad Thais out there. It has a chewy texture coupled with the distinctive sour taste that saves it from being too dense, a mistake many Thai places make too often. Coupled with the coconut milk soup and you just had a happier dinner than you might ask for.

I heard many locals longed to keep this place a secret, and I can see why. But seeing how much dedication this place poured into itself, I'd hate for it to go out of business. Felix advertises as a fine Fine French restaurant, charging prices that would reflect this.  We were expecting a nice dinner atmosphere yet found ourselves seated right next to the dance floor.  I had my head and back bumped multiple times.   I asked to speak to the manager who arrived and didn’t really care to hear my concerns about the extremely loud music and sitting at the edge of the bar turned dance part.  He said it’s been this way for 20 years and walked away. This restaurant takes your credit card information at the time of booking so you are stuck with no choice but, to stay and endure this frat party.  A group of 12 girls were littering dancing on their chairs at the table next to us.  A nice lady moved our seats half way through our entree and topped off our Prosecco.  I however, don’t feel I should have been charged a penny.  Our waiter never came back to see how we were but, I still gave him a 20% gratuity.

I would absolutely NOT recommend this unless you’re a 21 year old or one of the old creepy men there trying to pick them up.

Since 1991, this incredible spot has been more than just a restaurant-it's a hub for health, community, and passion. In this video, I speak with the manager about the restaurant's 33-year journey, its unique mission, and the vision of its founder, Angel. The full video is on Youtube, the link can be found in the link in my bio.
Caravan of Dreams isn't your typical vegan eatery. It stands out by offering completely natural, healthy dishes made from scratch-no processed
"Frankenstein" foods here! From medicinal mushroom-infused coffees to sugar- and dairy-free desserts that are unbelievably delicious, every menu item is crafted with care and packed with health benefits.
Beyond the food, this place fosters a sense of community in the heart of NYC, offering a welcoming environment where customers feel like family. Whether you're a long-time vegan or simply curious, Caravan of Dreams is a must-visit for anyone seeking nourishing food and a welcoming vibe.

Known for its warm ambiance and friendly staff, this cafe is a local favorite for those seeking a mix of traditional and modern Latin-inspired dishes.

The menu includes a variety of flavorful options, such as arepas, empanadas, and hearty breakfasts, each prepared with fresh ingredients and an emphasis on authenticity. Their coffee is also excellent, featuring rich, smooth brews that pair well with pastries or breakfast options. One of the standout items is their Venezuelan-style arepas, filled with perfectly seasoned meats and fresh toppings, which are both satisfying and delicious.

Tertulias also offers freshly-made juices and smoothies that add a refreshing touch, especially popular during the warmer months. The staff is welcoming, attentive, and happy to provide recommendations. Prices are reasonable, making it a great spot for a casual meal or coffee break. While the space is small and can get busy, especially on weekends, it adds to the charm and community feel of the place.

Overall, Tertulias Cafe Restaurant provides an authentic taste of Latin America in the heart of East Boston, making it a must-visit for both locals and newcomers.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'Tertulias Cafe in East Boston offers a cozy, inviting atmosphere and a menu that celebrates authentic Latin American flavors.
